You can keep it in one piece, or you cut it up if you are planning to throw it out. Remove the carpet in one piece. Pull it up in one corner, and work your way down one wall, pulling the carpet as you move. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/be/Remove-An-Indoor-Carpet-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Remove-An-Indoor-Carpet-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/be/Remove-An-Indoor-Carpet-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Remove-An-Indoor-Carpet-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Cut the carpet into strips if you are planning not to use it again. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2a/Remove-An-Indoor-Carpet-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Remove-An-Indoor-Carpet-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2a/Remove-An-Indoor-Carpet-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Remove-An-Indoor-Carpet-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Use a utility knife to cut strips of carpet. This will make it more manageable to remove. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/cc/Remove-An-Indoor-Carpet-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Remove-An-Indoor-Carpet-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/cc/Remove-An-Indoor-Carpet-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Remove-An-Indoor-Carpet-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Be careful not to cut too deeply. This is especially important if you have hardwood floors under the carpet that you are planning to refinish. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/78/Remove-An-Indoor-Carpet-Step-4Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Remove-An-Indoor-Carpet-Step-4Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/78/Remove-An-Indoor-Carpet-Step-4Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Remove-An-Indoor-Carpet-Step-4Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
